<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 93 / Government Bonds: Dealers disappointed by slight reduction
in Bundesbank repo
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SARA WEBB and JANE FULLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Bundesbank yesterday disappointed European government bond markets with
the announcement of a tiny easing at its weekly repo and some unfavourable
economic news. German government bonds fell back during the day, pulling the
other European markets lower.
The Bundesbank said the lowest allocated rate at its regular securities
repurchase tender had dropped to 8.09 per cent from 8.11 per cent, which
confirmed the recent very gradual easing in rates by the German central
bank.
The Bundesbank accepted bids for DM60.6bn of 14-day securities repurchase
funds, representing a net injection of DM5.8bn in liquidity.
Dealers had expected a drain of funds and a bigger reduction in the repo
rate, and the bund market fell back in the morning after the repo results
were announced.
Further disappointing news came with the announcement that the M3 money
supply aggregate expanded at a seasonally-adjusted, annualised 3.2 per cent
during the first three months of the year, having contracted in recent
months.
The central bank reported a February M3 contraction of 0.3 per cent
following January's contraction of 2.4 per cent. Dealers said the market was
particularly worried by the acceleration in bank lending.
Supply fears contributed to the market's doldrums after Mr Theo Waigel, the
German finance minister, was reported as saying the federal budget deficit
would be slightly more than DM65bn, compared with a DM39bn shortfall in
1992. The size of the deficit has raised worries in the market about the
amount of borrowing required.
In spite of the news, some dealers expressed faint hopes that the Bundesbank
might announce at cut in the Lombard rate at today's council meeting.
The Lombard rate - now 9 per cent - acts as a ceiling on overnight money
rates, while the 7.5 per cent discount rate provides the effective floor to
call money.
The Liffe bund future, which opened at 96.08, fell from its high of 96.13 to
a low of 95.66 before ending at around 95.68 in heavy volume.
UK government bonds lost between  1/8 and  1/4 of a point yesterday in the
middle and longer-dated maturities, taking their cue from the German bond
market.
Some of the sluggishness was attributed to residual disappointment over the
March public sector borrowing requirement and the rise in inflation,
announced in the past few days. The gilt market will be closely watching
today's labour market figures, including average earnings and unit labour
costs, for positive news.
Dealers added that some positioning was taking place ahead of the April 28
gilt auction.
JAPANESE government bonds rallied as the yen reached an historic high
against the dollar in Tokyo trading and the stock market continued to slip
back.
The yen touched 109.90 to the dollar, ending at 110.35 in Tokyo. The
strength of the yen against the dollar raised hopes of monetary easing,
dealers said.
The fall in the stock market, which closed lower for the fourth consecutive
day, also helped to lift bond futures. The Nikkei average index closed down
55.42 points at 19,773.01.
The futures contract, which was heavily traded, rose from its opening price
of 109.29 to a high of 109.45 before ending the day at 109.40.
In the cash market, the yield on the benchmark No 145 bond moved in a range
of 4.19 to 4.235 per cent, and closed at 4.225 per cent against its opening
level of 4.205 per cent.
Dealers said the new supply of 10-year bonds at Tuesday's auction was
probably the main explanation for the underperformance of the cash market.
US Treasury prices firmed slightly in dull trading yesterday as the market
patiently awaited more news on the economy.
In late trading the benchmark 30-year government bond was up  1/16 at 104
7/8, yielding 6.740 per cent. At the short end of the market, the two-year
note was also up  1/16 at 100 1/4, to yield 3.722 per cent.
The day opened quietly, with dealers and investors trading cautiously ahead
of the next set of economic data - today's weekly jobless claims report.
The only action in the morning was the Fed's buying of two-, three-, five-
and seven-year notes, apparently on behalf of the Bank of Japan. The
Japanese central bank had intervened earlier in the week to support the US
currency against the soaring yen. It was believed yesterday that the BoJ was
using those newly-acquired dollars to buy Treasury securities, via the Fed.
In the afternoon, the Treasury announced it would sell Dollars 15.25bn in
two-year and Dollars 11bn in five-year notes next week. The figures
surprised analysts, who had been expecting the Treasury to cut the size of
each issue.
</TEXT>
<XX>
