<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 93 / International Company News: Channel tunnel contractor claims
Dollars 360m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BOMBARDIER, the international aerospace and transit equipment group, has
lodged a CDollars 450m (USDollars 360m) claim with the prime contractor in
the Channel tunnel project, which is to link Britain and France, to cover
the cost of late design changes to 250 shuttle wagons it is building.
The prime contractor, TransManche Link, comprising a group of construction
companies, awarded Bombardier the CDollars 700m shuttle contract order three
years ago. The equipment is being built by Bombardier's Eurorail unit in
Europe.
TML itself is in dispute with Eurotunnel, the Channel tunnel owner, over
cost over-runs.
Bombardier halted output of wagons at Eurorail's Bruges plant in Belgium
nearly two months ago, saying it could not deliver because TML had not
provided certification for the first 10 prototypes.
Bombardier's claim is nearly twice industry estimates. Mr Laurent Baudoin,
chairman, said the claim would be subject to arbitration.
In the year ended last January, Bombardier earned C4132.8m, or 85 cents a
share. This was up 23 per cent from CDollars 107.7m, or 73 cents, a year
earlier. Revenues advanced to CDollars 4.4bn, against CDollars 3.1bn.
The revenue increase partly reflected an acquisition. All parts of the
business did better except transit equipment which posted a loss of CDollars
73m before tax.
Fourth-quarter earnings were CDollars 42.1m, or 27 cents, against CDollars
37m, or 24 cents, a year earlier.
Talisman Energy, formerly BP Canada, had first-quarter earnings of CDollars
7.9m, or 16 cents a share, against Dollars 2m, or 4 cents, a year earlier.
Revenues were Dollars 63m, against Dollars 53.5m.
</TEXT>
