<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 93 / International Company News: Unexpected shortfall at Data
General
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
DATA GENERAL, the US minicomputer manufacturer, reported unexpected losses
for the second quarter as its struggle to achieve sustained profitability
faltered, despite increased sales of its new open systems products.
Net losses for the quarter were Dollars 7.6m, or 22 cents per share,
compared with losses of Dollars 55.3m, or Dollars 1.69 per share, in the
same period last year when the company took a restructuring charge of
Dollars 48m.
Revenues for the quarter were Dollars 267.4m, compared with Dollars 273.8m.
The company said that without the unfavourable impact of foreign exchange
rate changes, revenue would have been slightly higher than last year.
'We are not satisfied with the overall results, primarily in the revenue
area,' said Mr Ronald Skates, president and chief executive, 'but we are
encouraged by the continued success of our open systems computers.'
Data General is in the midst of a transition from its traditional
proprietary minicomputer products to open systems based upon industry
standards. Revenues for these open systems showed significant growth in the
quarter, Mr Skates said.
Wall Street analysts had been expecting Data General to report profits of
around 4 cents per share. The company's stock closed at Dollars 9 1/2 in New
York yesterday, down from Tuesday's close of Dollars 10 1/4 .
For the first six months of fiscal 1993, the company reported a net loss of
Dollars 6.8m, or 20 cents per share, compared with a net loss of Dollars
51.3m, or Dollars 1.58 per share, including the restructuring charge.
Revenues for the first half were Dollars 547.1m, down from Dollars 568.6m in
the same period last year.
'We are confident that our open-systems strategy is in line with the needs
of the marketplace,' said Mr Skates. 'However, we continue to be very
cautious for the short-term in light of the continuing weak worldwide
economy and because we see no evidence that industry-wide pricing pressures
will abate in the near future.'
</TEXT>
