<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 93 / International Company News: Underlying improvement lifts
Whirlpool to Dollars 58m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHIRLPOOL, the world's biggest maker of large home appliances, yesterday
reported an underlying improvement in first-quarter profits, at Dollars 58m,
up from Dollars 35m in the same period of 1992.
However, two charges meant that the bottom-line figure for the
Michigan-based group showed a Dollars 162m loss after tax in the most recent
three months.
One of these was a Dollars 180m item, related to accounting rule changes;
the second was a Dollars 40m charge to adjust the value of certain accounts
held by Whirlpool Financial Corporation.
Whirlpool had warned the stock market of the Dollars 40m item.
Whirlpool's first-quarter sales rose by 5 per cent to Dollars 1.81bn, and Mr
David Whitwam, chairman, described operating performance as 'excellent'.
The company said shipments in the North American market outpaced the
industry average of about 3 per cent, and operating profits grew even more
substantially.
In Europe, shipments rose only slightly, but margins increased. In Latin
America and Asia, there was a 'marked' advance in both shipments and
revenues.
The Brazilian affiliates also swung into profit, having suffered losses a
year ago.
</TEXT>
