<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 93 / International Company News: Amoco records earnings of
Dollars 229m in first quarter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AMOCO, the Chicago-based energy company, yesterday reported a net profit of
Dollars 229m, or 46 cents per share, for the first quarter of 1993, which
compares with a loss of Dollars 619m, or Dollars 1.25 per share, in the
year-ago quarter.
At the operating level, Amoco earned Dollars 343m, or 69 cents, in the first
quarter of 1993, but this excluded Dollars 170m of write-downs from
exploration in the Congo and tax benefits of Dollars 56m derived from asset
disposals.
The comparable 1992 operating figure was Dollars 257m, or 52 cents, before
Dollars 924m of charges resulting from accounting changes and tax benefits
of Dollars 48m.
Amoco's first-quarter revenues were Dollars 6.978bn, up slightly from
Dollars 56.389bn a year ago.
Mr Laurance Fuller, Amoco chairman, said that, exclusive of the special
items, the company's earnings benefited from cost-reduction efforts.
He said US exploration and production operations also improved, reflecting
higher natural gas and crude oil prices and higher gas volumes.
Worldwide capital and exploration spending in the quarter declined to
Dollars 597m from Dollars 634m in the first quarter of last year.
The company is planning to spend Dollars 1.5bn to develop a large oilfield
in the South China Sea, in an area 120 miles south-east of Hong Kong.
Schlumberger, the energy industry services group, yesterday unveiled a net
loss of Dollars 114.8m in the first quarter of 1993, compared with a net
profit of Dollars 156.3m a year ago.
The company said the loss was caused by a Dollars 248m extraordinary debit
resulting from the adoption of new accounting standards.
Excluding the special charge Schlumberger would have had profits of Dollars
133.2m, down by 15 per cent year-on-year.
Revenues in the 1993 quarter were Dollars 1.62bn, up slightly from Dollars
1.59bn a year ago.
</TEXT>
