<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 93 / UK Company News: ACCBank rises 31% to IPounds 8.5m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ACCBANK, the state-run Irish concern being groomed for privatisation,
reported a 31 per cent increase in pre-tax profits, from IPounds 6.51m to
IPounds 8.5m (Pounds 8.41m), in the 1992 year.
Established in 1927 to provide exclusively agricultural loans, the bank has
in the past five years diversified its operations and now trades as an
ordinary high street bank.
It has 45 branches throughout Ireland and a deposit base which expanded last
year by 21 per cent to IPounds 592m.
Interest and other income grew by 19 per cent to IPounds 95.7m (IPounds
80.4m). Total assets rose by 26 per cent to IPounds 860m (IPounds 681m).
The 1992 dividend of IPounds 763,000 goes to the Irish Government, which is
the 100 per cent shareholder.
Last August, Mr Bertie Ahern, the finance minister, announced that the
government intended to dispose of ACC. However, those plans have seemingly
been put on hold with the formation of the Labour-Fianna Fail coalition in
January, which in its programme for government talked of a merger with ICC,
another state-run bank, rather than a privatisation.
</TEXT>
