<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 93 / UK Company News: Dorothy Perkins director quits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BURTON, the UK fashion retail group, is expected to announce today that Mr
John Coleman, managing director of the Dorothy Perkins chain, has left the
company because of differences of management style.
But there were rumours within the retail trade last night that Mr Coleman
had been asked to leave after Mr John Hoerner, Burton chief executive,
discovered he had been in discussions with headhunters about other senior
positions - including that of chief executive of the Storehouse group.
Storehouse has been without a chief executive since the resignation of Mr
David Dworkin, who left in February to join the US department store group
Carter Hawley Hale in California. Storehouse has been looking on both sides
of the Atlantic for a replacement.
Mr Coleman last night refused to make any comment on the speculation.
If he were to be appointed to the Storehouse position, it would be a rapid
rise for a man who entered the retail trade only 10 years ago.
However, in the past two years Mr Coleman has helped make Dorothy Perkins
one of Burton's two best-performing divisions, along with the Debenhams
department store chain, redefining its image and target customers and
introducing a new store format which boosted sales.
</TEXT>
