<DATE>930422
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 93 / Compaq triples sales of its PCs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
COMPAQ Computer doubled its first-quarter sales and earnings and tripled the
number of PCs shipped.
'The company's performance in the first quarter was driven by record demand
for our products from a broad base of customers,' said Mr Eckhard Pfeiffer,
president and chief executive.
Net income in the quarter jumped to Dollars 102m (Pounds 67m) or Dollars
1.23 per share, from Dollars 45m or 53 cents per share while revenues
increased 106 per cent to Dollars 1.6bn from Dollars 783m.
Net earnings were boosted by a lower tax rate. The company said it had
adopted an international investment strategy that has lowered its estimated
tax rate to 24 per cent, from 33 per cent in the first quarter last year.
Analysts said the expansion of the company's manufacturing operations in
Singapore would lower its effective tax rate.
'We achieved these record results while driving down operating expenses,' Mr
Pfeiffer added. Operating expenses were down in absolute terms as well as a
percentage of revenues, the company said.
'Our challenge is to sustain our growth and maintain our focus on improved
profitability by closely managing our gross margins and tightly controlling
expenses.'
Mr Daryl White, Compaq chief financial officer, said market growth had been
stronger in North America than in international markets. In Europe revenues
increased by 59 per cent to Dollars 673m in the first quarter, but this was
the lowest regional growth rate. North American sales were up 159 per cent
at Dollars 795m.
Last year Compaq moved aggressively into the Japanese market, offering PCs
at prices well below those of Japanese producers. In March, it launched 39
new PCs , and demand for these models has been particularly high, the
company said, although shortages of several components have constrained its
ability to keep up with demand.
Mr White said Compaq was optimistic that sales will remain strong throughout
1993, despite predictions from analysts that growth in PC sales will slow
down. 'We are planning for slower growth, but based on first quarter
momentum it doesn't seem likely,' he said. 'We have a large backlog of
orders.'
