<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Heseltine sees dilemma on PO
privatisation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Michael Heseltine, the trade and industry secretary, admitted in the
Commons yesterday that the government faced a 'dilemma' over the
privatisation of the post office.
He explained that the problem at the heart of the matter was that of
honouring pledges that the universality of price and service provided in all
parts of the country was 'non-negotiable', while relieving the post office
of the constraints imposed by the public sector so that it could become more
competitive.
Mr Heseltine rejected a demand by Mr Robin Cook, the shadow trade and
industry secretary, that the whole idea should be dropped following the
recent disclosure that the necessary legislation would not be introduced in
the next parliamentary session.
Two Tory backbenchers, Mr David Nicholson (Taunton) and Mr Patrick Cormack
(Staffordshire South), expressed reservations about changing the post
office's present status.
Mr Simon Hughes, for the Liberal Democrats, urged a relaxation of the
constraints associated with the public sector and insisted that 'privatising
the post office would be a privatisation too far'.
Mr Heseltine accused Mr Hughes of providing a classic example of 'trying to
have it both ways'.
As for it being a privatisation too far, he emphasised: 'We will decide
whether we are going to embark on the journey or not'.
Mr Heseltine described suggestions that the post office could be given
commercial freedom without being privatised as being divorced from the
reality of public sector accounting.
He said: 'There has never been a government which has been able to set free
a public sector enterprise outside the discipline of the public expenditure
round and Treasury control.'
Mr Heseltine also stressed that the post office was coming under increasing
competition from technology such as fax machines and courier services.
In a written reply Sir John Cope, paymaster general, cited 'commercial
confidentiality' when refusing to disclose the additional costs incurred by
the post office as a result of the recent VAT changes in the treatment of
intra-EC freight transport services.
Mr Tim Eggar, the energy minister, yesterday urged British Coal to move
'rapidly' to place on the market mines like Bevercotes in Nottinghamshire
which it no longer requires.
Mr Richard Alexander (C Newark) complained that private sector interests
were not being given an early opportunity to view mines which British Coal
planned to close at the end of the month.
</TEXT>
