<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Letter highlights Labour fears on
housing benefit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FUTURE arrangements for housing benefit for housing association tenants
facing rent rises are in doubt, Labour said yesterday, following a
minister's refusal to guarantee that increases would be met.
Mr John Battle, the opposition housing spokesman, highlighted the issue
after a letter from Mr Alistair Burt, the junior social security minister,
earlier this month.
On housing association rents, Mr Burt wrote: 'Although the Housing Benefit
scheme can meet reasonable rents in full (and reasonable rent increases if
the customer is in receipt of benefit), it cannot be assumed that housing
benefit will automatically increase to meet housing association rent
increases'.
The question has been given added force by the cut in housing association
grant and the government's drive towards market rents.
Mr Battle attacked the government for allowing the two departments involved
 -the Department of Social Security and the Department of the Environment -
to contradict each other.
'At present the housing minister says social security will pay - something
the social security minister has just denied. As housing association rents
are already escalating, tenants have a right to know how they are to meet
the cost of the increases,' he said.
The letter reflects the tension between the two departments over aspects of
housing policy in this area.
One of the aims of the inter-departmental review of housing benefit is to
resolve the problem of the effect of the DOE's plans for improving
conditions for council and housing association tenants, at the cost of
higher rents, on the DSS budget which bears much of the impact through
housing benefit spending.
</TEXT>
