<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 93 / Parliament and Politics: ICI chairman defends job units
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A COMMONS committee yesterday suggested that shareholders of Imperial
Chemicals Industries (ICI) might force the group to disband units that help
redundant staff find new jobs if they were more aware of their activities
and associated costs.
Sir Denys Henderson, chairman of ICI, told the employment committee that the
company - which employs 50,000 people today compared with 140,000 in 1970 -
had redeployment units on its sites. These helped employees being made
redundant find alternative employment, both inside the group and externally.
The units are successful - at ICI Agro-Chemicals 80 per cent of the
division's staff affected by redundancies over the past two years have had
new jobs within six months.
Sir Denys agreed with the committee that the Employment Service did a
similar job - but he said that it came in at a later time when the
individual was jobless.
Labour MP Mr Ernie Ross said he would like his committee to recommend more
in-house units like those at ICI. But he was worried that if the job units
were given such prominence in a government report 'greedy' ICI shareholders
might call for their abolition. Sir Denys said the sums spent on the units
were 'relatively modest' and that he had no such fears.
</TEXT>
