<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Major to hold TV press meetings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN Major is planning to hold occasional televised press conferences at
Downing Street, which could possibly be broadcast live, Ralph Atkins writes.
The prime minister's office said yesterday that Mr Major sees the move as a
chance to get his message across more directly. However it stressed that
they would not be held on a regular basis.
Mr Major does not believe the 'bear pit' atmosphere of his twice-weekly
Commons questions sessions allow for a calm explanation of his thinking. He
is also instinctively wary of the lobby system of unattributable briefings
and press conferences could be used particularly when the Commons is in
recess.
The prime minister's office also said yesterday that Mr Major wants to 'grab
the agenda' on the development of the European Community after Maastricht in
a series of speeches starting today.
Britain has too often been forced into responding to an agenda set by the
France-Germany alliance, an official said: 'We have been left rather
dragging our heels.'
Mr Major will develop his theme of an enlarged, free market European
Community when he addresses the Conservative Group on Europe tonight - a
meeting marking the 20th anniversary of Britain's entry into the EC.
</TEXT>
