<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 93 / Barclays may not pass on rate cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BARCLAYS BANK yesterday indicated that it would not pass on base rate cuts
to business borrowers if the base rate, now 6 per cent, falls below 5 per
cent.
The bank announced that it was cutting the minimum interest rate for its
200,000 business borrowers from 6 per cent plus the customer's lending
margin to 5 per cent plus margin. But Mr Bill Gordon, banking division
managing director, said any further reduction in the bank's minimum interest
rates 'would make it difficult to provide its depositors with a satisfactory
return'.
National Westminster, the other leading lender to small and medium-sized
businesses, has already indicated it may not pass on base rate cuts below 5
per cent, saying that a decision on whether to do so would depend on
personal savings rates.
Both banks have been careful to reduce minimum rates in advance of base rate
cuts over the past year.
They have faced controversy - and a Bank of England inquiry - over the
passing on of interest rate cuts.
</TEXT>
