<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 93 / Management 'shambles' admitted at health authority
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANAGEMENT PROBLEMS in the West Midlands Regional Health Authority resulted
in at least Pounds 10m-worth of expenditure for which little or no value was
received, a report to the Commons public accounts committee said yesterday.
MPs on the committee have been examining aspects of the authority's
administration since a district auditor's report last year concluded that a
consultancy exercise designed to save Pounds 50m had cost up to Pounds 4m.
Sir Duncan Nichol, National Health Service chief executive, yesterday
admitted that the overall situation revealed by the auditor had been a
'shambles'. He accepted that his NHS management executive should have become
aware of the West Midlands problems sooner than it did.
Following the consultancy investigation, the district auditor carried out
further inquiries and concludes in a report that the authority was suffering
from 'general management problems'. The report finds that the authority's
board failed to exert sufficient control.
A decision by the board to set up a separate regionally managed services
division to oversee peripheral activities, says the report, was valid. But
the board's subsequent action in leaving the division's director to operate
without effective direction and control was an 'unacceptable abrogation of
responsibility'.
The then regional general manager had failed to report significant
developments to the board or control the actions of senior officers. 'Many
of the RHA's management controls did not work. The arrangements set up to
monitor internal activities failed to identify problems and did not
facilitate prompt action when it was needed.'
Numerous developments had depended on business plans that were 'uniformly
speculative and unrealistic'. Neither the board nor senior officers
reappraised plans in the light of changing circumstances.
The report says financial control at the health authority had fallen below
the standards generally expected of a public body.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
