<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 93 / Private investors urged to buy gilts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Bank of England is taking steps to encourage private-investor purchases
in gilts as the government battles to fund its growing budget deficit,
Philip Coggan writes.
For the forthcoming auction of 7 1/4 per cent Treasury stock 1998, the Bank
will be publishing for the first time shortened application forms in the
national press. These are designed specially for private investors making
so-called non-competitive bids - where the price is set by the market.
The Bank said falling inflation and interest rates had increased
private-investor enthusiasm for gilts. It did not want to mount an
aggressive mass-marketing campaign for gilts but it could provide
information and easy dealing facilities.
To meet the first objective the Bank published a free booklet earlier this
month to explain the intricacies of gilts to the small investor. About
60,000 people have requested the guide, and some 300,000 booklets have been
placed in post offices.
To improve dealing facilities, the Treasury recently increased to Pounds
25,000 the amount of stock which could be bought via the cheap dealing
service at post offices.
Investing in gilts - a guide for the small investor. Available from post
offices or by phoning 0800 616814.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
