<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 93 / Governance changes 'not productive'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LATEST innovations in corporate governance have had little effect in
improving the performance of British business, according to a study released
today.
It says that adding non-executive directors to the board or splitting the
roles of chairman and chief executive, as the recent Cadbury committee on
corporate governance recommended, have hardly any impact on earnings per
share or other key financial indicators.
The study comes in the latest edition of the Corporate Register published by
Hemmington Scott, the information group, and covers all 1,533 UK-quoted
companies, excluding investment trusts.
Mr Peter Scott, who co-ordinated the research, said: 'One can't point to any
empirical evidence that this kind of governance has made any practical
difference. I think the jury is out.'
Sir Adrian Cadbury, chairman of the Cadbury committee, said use of the
indicators referred to was 'superficial' and gave no indication of the
quality of the non-executive directors involved.
The research does not consider the non-financial benefits which
non-executive directors might bring to a board. But the Cadbury committee's
voluntary code relies on shareholders to exert pressure on companies for
better corporate governance.
The findings indicate that they have little financial incentive to lobby for
these changes. The study shows that for the median-quoted British company
there was no earnings per share growth over the past five years, but for the
median company, with a combined chairman and chief executive, reported
earnings increased by 1.7 per cent.
For the best-performing quarter of companies earnings per share rose 12.6
per cent, but the figure was up 13.9 per cent for companies with no
non-executives and 13.4 per cent for those with a combined chairman and
chief executive.
Just 8 per cent of quoted companies now have no non-executive directors and
only 21 per cent have a combined chairman and chief executive, the study
shows.
Arthur Andersen Corporate Register. Hemmington Scott, City Innovation
Centre, 26-31 Whiskin St, London EC1R 0BP. Pounds 150 a year.
</TEXT>
<XX>
