<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 93 / Fears on jobs plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SCEPTICISM about whether employers will take part in the government's new
Workstart programme has been expressed by the independent Employment Policy
Institute.
Workstart, under which employers will be given a government subsidy of
Pounds 60 a week for taking on the long-term jobless, was announced in last
month's Budget. The institute said: 'The most immediate task facing those
responsible for the pilots will be to gain the interest of employers.'
It suggests that the pilot schemes should experiment with different levels
of subsidies in the range of Pounds 60 to Pounds 150 a week.
It also said that problems had arisen with previous job subsidy experiments,
including the displacement of existing workers and the provision of
subsidies for workers who would have been taken on anyway - 71 per cent of
the subsidised recruits under a 1978 experiment would have been taken on
without the subsidy.
