<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 93 / Housing grant cut may be reviewed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT is prepared to reconsider its plan to cut grants to housing
associations to build or buy homes for rent, Sir George Young, housing
minister, indicated yesterday.
The plan, announced in the chancellor's Autumn Statement, would have cut the
grant from an average last year of 72 per cent of the cost of new housing to
60 per cent next year and 55 per cent in 1995. The balance is raised on the
capital markets.
Questioned by the cross-party Commons environment committee, Sir George said
reducing the grant to 55 per cent by 1995 was a 'target', not a
'commitment', and would be reconsidered if the cuts looked likely to force
up rents unduly or to make it harder for associations to attract the private
finance they need.
Some financial institutions had warned that associations would find it
difficult to borrow 45 per cent of the cost against the security of a
tenanted home.
The extra interest charges would have pushed up rents by 70 per cent
according to a study by stockbrokers UBS Phillips &amp; Drew.
The National Federation of Housing Associations said these rises would have
left up to 85 per cent of tenants dependent on housing benefit.
Sir George said he was prepared to see some rise in rents, especially if the
economic recovery raised incomes. The increasing proportion of tenants on
housing benefit indicated that the housing budget was better targeted on
those most in need.
However, no decision had yet been made on the level of housing association
grant for the next two years.
Sir George said he would make a judgment later in the summer about the grant
rate for next year after consulting financial institutions about their
readiness to fund associations at given rates.
Sir George also said that there were no plans to change the legislation on
government grants to enable them to be paid to private property developers.
The minister said he had an open mind on the desirability of such a change
and would welcome views from MPs.
However, he would want to be satisfied on questions such as the
accountability of developers for public money and the level of rents.
</TEXT>
