<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 93 / Tanker route scheme attacked
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A GOVERNMENT plan for a traffic separation scheme for the sea route between
Fair Isle and the southern tip of Shetland, scene of the Braer tanker
disaster earlier this year, was unnecessary, ill-conceived and could be
counter-productive, professional mariners told the Donaldson inquiry
yesterday.
The criticism came from two witnesses appearing for the Nautical Institute,
an international body with 6,000 members in 100 countries, on the second day
of the hearing investigating the wider implications of the Braer disaster.
Captain Peter Russell, an experienced pilot and institute fellow, said he
could see no advantage in the plan, which would require expensive radar
surveillance equipment to be effective.
He said too few ships used the channel to justify special routing
procedures.
He said: 'If you put it in when it is not needed mariners will treat it with
derision.'
Mr Julian Parker, institute secretary, said that in cases such as the Braer
accident better ship-to-shore communications and a faster response time by
the emergency ser-vices were the key to pre-venting pollution, not the
presence of radar surveil-lance.
The two institute witnesses voiced concern over declining standards among
crews, growing problems with safety equipment and increasingly frequent
mechanical breakdowns, which now account for a quarter of all large tanker
'casual-ties'.
The inquiry, being held in London, also heard that there are growing
problems with communications at sea where English is meant to be the
international language.
The inquiry continues.
</TEXT>
