FT  22 APR 93 / Rail union fails to settle dispute
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE rail dispute remained unresolved last night. After nine hours of
discussion the executive of the RMT, the main rail union, failed to reach a
decision on whether to support or reject British Rail's final proposals to
resolve a conflict which has already brought two one-day shutdowns of the
network.
An RMT spokesman said the dispute remained 'unresolved'.
The executive will resume its deliberations today but it remained unclear
last night whether this would produce any definitive verdict on BR's peace
plan.
The RMT executive appears to be evenly split between those who want to
settle and those who wish to press ahead with more disruption in the
campaign to achieve a guarantee of no compulsory redundancies and a
moratorium on the extension of contract work.
Mr Paul Watkinson, BR employee-relations director, said the BR board had
gone as far as it could to meet the union's demands.
The BR document presented to the union leadership late on Tuesday night
confirmed that it does 'not foresee the need for compulsory redundancy among
its existing general staff during the next couple of years, providing there
is opportunity for voluntary severance and staff avail themselves of the
opportunities for redeployment and retraining spelled out in the various
agreements'.
