<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 93 / Stonehenge 'a national disgrace'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government's stewardship of Britain's historic buildings and monuments
was last night slammed by an influential committee of MPs which warned that
up to 2,400 of the finest examples were at risk.
The MPs of the Commons public accounts committee said that the position at
Stonehenge, a site of national and international significance, could only be
described as a 'disgrace'.
The committee's report directs its fire at the National Heritage Department
and English Heritage, the main government-sponsored body responsible for
preserving listed buildings and national monuments.
It acknowledges that both have announced plans to greatly improve their
stewardship. But it adds: 'We are concerned that the physical condition of
up to 2,400 properties in the highest Grade I and Grade II categories could
be at risk.'
In a blunt warning the MPs add: 'We expect the department and English
Heritage to establish the full extent of the risk to such properties and the
priorities for repair and preservation as the basis for an action plan to
remedy the position as soon as possible.'
Turning to the 'national disgrace' of Stonehenge, the report says that
English Heritage had acknowledged all the public criticism of the condition
of the site. It was seeking more money from the government to implement
improvements.
More generally it talks of 'protracted delay and indecision' in the
improvement of heritage records, a seven-year slippage in the target date
for the listing of all monuments, and the absence of any clear action plan
to preserve the heritage they represent.
The MPs say that the National Heritage Department must ensure that
individual properties are only transferred into public ownership if
sufficient funds are guaranteed for their future care. At the same time
local authorities and government needed to be much more vigorous in
enforcing repairs on listed buildings in private ownership.
</TEXT>
<XX>
