<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 93 / Businesses report recovery in Wales and east Midlands
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM and PAUL CHEESERIGHT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE RECOVERY appears to be under way in Wales and the Bristol region,
according to quarterly economic surveys to be published today. A chamber of
commerce business trends survey also suggests a return of confidence to the
east Midlands.
In Wales, 71 per cent of manufacturing companies surveyed for the Wales
Chamber of Commerce expect turnover to improve in the next 12 months - the
most positive finding for several years. A total of 57 per cent of companies
in the service sector expect an improvement, and in both sectors only 8 per
cent visualise a fall.
Hopes for higher profitability are also rising, with 54 per cent of
manufacturers and 44 per cent of service companies expecting to see this.
'The financial picture across Wales is one which shows that confidence is
returning to the economy,' said Mr Graham Hall, leading executive of the
chamber.
The Wales chamber says that cashflow is a cause of concern, with nearly a
third of companies reporting a deterioration. The warning is repeated by
Bristol Chamber of Commerce and Initiative, which points out that more
businesses are likely to fail in the early stages of recovery than in the
depths of recession. The Bristol chamber also warns that the recovery may be
weak at first.
The chamber reports that, of about 400 businesses surveyed in Bristol and
the surrounding area, 36 per cent of manufacturing companies and 39 per cent
of those in the service sector said there had been a rise in domestic sales,
compared with about a quarter reporting a fall. Orders showed a similar
finding.
On export sales, the balance was even more positive and on export orders,
the chamber says, 'the picture is one of continuous improvement with
manufacturing companies increasingly bullish'.
The chamber sees signs that the rise in unemployment may be flattening.
There are similar findings in Wales. During the three months, 42 per cent of
the 600 Welsh companies surveyed reported that UK sales were the same as in
the previous quarter and a third said there had been an improvement. Export
orders are more buoyant with nearly half the manufacturers reporting a rise.
Nearly 30 per cent of smaller businesses expect to recruit labour in the
next quarter.
Confidence has apparently also started to seep back into the east Midlands
economy. More than half the companies taking part in the latest business
trends survey of the regional chambers of commerce expect turnover to
improve and slightly less than half expecting profitability to increase.
The survey, published yesterday and covering 450 companies in one of the
most economically diverse of the UK regions, shows that recovery is
potential rather than actual.
The proportion of companies operating at full capacity in March was 5
percentage points lower than last December at 22 per cent. Although there is
some indication that companies are beginning to revise upwards their
investment intentions and 30 per cent of companies, against 24 per cent last
December, reported improved cashflow, order books have been at best stable.
During the last three months there has been a modest improvement in export
orders, with 38 per cent reporting an increase in March compared with 36 per
cent in December.
In the aftermath of sterling's departure last September from the exchange
rate mechanism, half the companies surveyed said the price of materials was
their main worry, replacing concern with lower interest rates.
</TEXT>
