<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 93 / Employers' bodies seek one voice
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Confederation of British Industry and the Engineering Employers'
Federation yesterday announced a fresh attempt to work together more closely
in a move to create stronger and more effective links between industry and
the government.
The two industrial organisations are commissioning McKinsey and Company, the
consultants, to identify ways in which industry can better represent itself.
The announcement raised speculation that the study could be the first step
in a merger of the two bodies. The federation, and most of its large
members, belong to the CBI, but one observer said yesterday: 'It's not a
takeover.'
The two bodies held exploratory talks in 1991 to identify a basis for
greater collaboration but these fell through. To the federation's surprise
the CBI then set up its own National Manufacturing Council, with which the
federation has been co-operating.
With two new heads appointed since 1991 - Mr Howard Davies at the CBI and Mr
Neil Johnson at the federation - it was considered sensible to re-examine
closer links.
The two bodies said: 'We hope this study will lead to a stronger voice for
industry, the closest possible collaboration between two leading industrial
organisations, and improved services to our members.'
McKinsey will start work immediately and is expected to make a preliminary
report in June.
Officials of the two bodies yesterday described the status of the
discussions as preliminary, so it was not possible to say exactly where they
would lead. However both are clearly attaching some importance to the study.
A steering group has been set up to guide it, made up of Mr Noel Davies,
chief executive of VSEL Consortium; Mr Ian Dixon, chairman of Willmott
Dixon; Mr Tony Hales, chief executive of Allied Lyons; Sir David Lees,
chairman and chief executive of GKN; Mr Graham Mackenzie, chief executive of
United Engineering Steels; and Mr Nigel Whittaker, group corporate affairs
director at Kingfisher.
</TEXT>
