<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 93 / Supermarket queue times 'could be cut'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CUSTOMER QUEUEING times at some supermarket checkouts could be cut by up to
a third if checkout counters were redesigned, according to research carried
out by the University of Birmingham.
At the same time, many of the illnesses and injuries suffered by operators
could be avoided if checkouts were designed according to simple ergonomic
principles, the research found.
Supermarket customers interviewed by the researchers reported irritation if
they were delayed by more than a couple of minutes. This was particularly
the case when the operator was unable to serve because a previous customer
was still packing shopping.
Many shoppers suggested longer counters so they could unpack all their items
while the previous customer's shopping was being scanned and paid for.
Two thirds of customers wanted their shopping to be packed for them, with
some saying it ought to be part of the service. Elderly people and shoppers
with small children particularly wanted help. Few supermarkets in the UK
offer packing, in contrast to the US where it is normal for customers to
have their goods packed and carried to the car by staff.
About one third of operators questioned experienced work-related aches or
pains even before they started their shift; by the end of the shift, two
thirds reported discomfort.
The main problems were found to be work surfaces and equipment positioned so
high that operators had to work with raised shoulders; inadequate leg
clearance beneath counters; and inappropriate seating. Reaching and lifting
items for scanning and packing, and bending and reaching under the counter
for bags were the two tasks that caused the most problems.
Developments in technology in recent years mean that operators can typically
deal with 800 or more items of shopping an hour. However, the researchers
found that some poorly-sited scanning equipment meant that operators
experienced greater discomfort and had to slow down.
Mr Terry Fielding, managing director of Potrafke, the checkout manufacturer
which commissioned the research, said it was estimated that productivity
gains of 15 per cent to 30 per cent could be achieved without much
difficulty if the ergonomic principles highlighted by the report were
applied.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P5411 Grocery Stores.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Services &amp; Services use.
</TP>
