<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 93 / Sir Philip Shelbourne: Obituary
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR Philip Shelbourne, who died last Thursday aged 68, was a merchant banker
and chairman of Britoil, the largest oil exploration group operating in the
North Sea until it was taken over by British Petroleum in 1988.
Sir Philip started his career as a barrister, moving to a partnership at
Rothschilds merchant bank in 1962. He was chairman of Samuel Montagu when he
was appointed chairman of the British National Oil Corporation in 1980.
Sir Philip enjoyed power and influence, according to close associates, and
his appointment to the corporation was controversial because of his lack of
industry experience. Sir Alastair Morton, the corporation's managing
director at the time and now chairman of Eurotunnel, resigned.
The government sold 51 per cent of the corporation to the public in 1982,
with the rest sold three years later. This left it vulnerable to takeover
and BP launched a hostile bid in 1987. When BP was successful, Sir Philip
retired.
But in the course of the takeover bid the terms of his contract with Britoil
became public, causing a furore. His retirement package included a Pounds
40,000-a-year salary and a Pounds 92-a-day lunch allow-ance.
It was widely seen as a symbol of corporate excess at a time when oil
companies were strapped for cash. BP terminated the package when it took
over the company.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P99   Nonclassifiable Establishments.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
