<DATE>930422
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 93 / Homes Assured 'slid into chaos' before collapse
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DIRECTORS of Homes Assured, the mortgage brokers, allowed the company to
trade fraudulently for nine months before it collapsed with debts of Pounds
9m in 1989, the Old Bailey was told yesterday.
From the outset, Homes Assured, which was set up to arrange mortgages for
council tenants buying their own homes, was never adequately capitalised and
its finances soon slid into chaos, said Mr Michael Kalisher QC, prosecuting
for the Serious Fraud Office.
By November 1988, Homes Assured was hopelessly insolvent and should have
stopped trading, he said. The company avoided one attempt by creditors to
put it into liquidation by showing a court bogus accounts. It also took out
short-term loans and stopped paying staff wages and other bills in an
attempt to survive.
However, such attempts only delayed the inevitable and the company was
forced into liquidation in August 1989, Mr Kalisher told the court.
He was opening the prosecution of Mr Anthony Dobson, a former Homes Assured
director, Mr Michael Robinson, the company's managing director and Mr Keith
Woodward, another director.
Mr Dobson faces three counts of fraudulent trading, Mr Robinson two similar
charges and Mr Woodward one of fraudulent trading and one of furnishing
false information. All deny the charges.
After the company was set up in late 1987, it was supported with Pounds
250,000 in capital from the Bank of Boston, Mr Kalisher said. To attract
this investment, Mr Dobson lied by withholding the information that he had
averted personal bankruptcy by reaching a voluntary agreement with creditors
to repay debts of Pounds 600,000. The bank would not have made this
investment had it known of his personal circumstances.
Homes Assured initially appeared solvent, but the absence of genuine profits
was concealed by the large advance payments it received in commissions from
life assurance policies sold.
However, its troubles mounted when commissions on cancelled policies had to
be returned, overheads rose unchecked and its tied agency status with the
Legal &amp; General was lost.
'Each of the defendants knew when they continued to trade after November
that there was no real prospect of Homes Assured paying these debts. They
continued to trade despite that and intentionally defrauded the creditors of
Homes Assured or its subsidiaries,' said Mr Kalisher.
Sir Edward du Cann, the former Tory MP and chairman of the Conservative
party, was a vice-chairman and director of the company and played an active
role in raising finance, Mr Kalisher said. However, he would not be called
to give evidence.
The trial, which is expected to last about four months, continues today.
</TEXT>
