<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 93 / US to set training standards: National vocational standards
considered
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Clinton administration yesterday announced a series of educational and
training reforms including plans for a new national system of vocational
qualifications along European lines.
The Dollars 420m package, known as Goals 2000: Educate America Act, is
intended to help the US achieve 'world class' educational standards by
defining more precisely what students need to learn, improving assessment
techniques and introducing new forms of certification for non-graduates.
It differs from initiatives launched by the Bush administration mainly in
putting no emphasis on efforts to increase parental choice or competition
between schools.
Mr Robert Reich, the labour secretary, said he was setting up a national
skills standards board consisting of business, labour and educational
leaders to 'identify essential occupational skills and create a voluntary
system of standards, assessments and certification'.
The plan was to bring the US into line with other industrialised countries
by creating a set of nationally recognised credentials for the three
quarters of the population that lacks college degrees.
Mr Richard Riley, the education secretary, announced the formation of a
national educational standards and improvement council to oversee school
reforms.
The council would set 'contents standards' defining what students should
know and be able to do in each subject area and devise assessments to
measure student achievement and school performance. The standards and
assessments would be voluntary, reflecting states' primary responsibility
for education under the US constitution.
</TEXT>
