<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 93 / Brazil opts to keep its president
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BILL HINCHBERGER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAO PAULO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BRAZILIAN voters yesterday decided overwhelmingly to keep the country's
presidential system, according to exit polls. Voting in a binding
plebiscite, they also opted to maintain a republican form of government
rather than revert to a monarchy.
The DataFolha polling service indicated that 58 per cent had favoured a
presidential system, against 26 per cent for the parliamentary option; 16
per cent rejected both choices. The republican option secured 71 per cent,
according to its exit poll, while only 11 per cent wanted a monarchy.
Political leaders who campaigned for a parliamentary system accepted defeat
early, partly because polls consistently predicted a big victory for the
presidential system.
Many opinion leaders said that political reforms had to move ahead even
though the system of government would remain the same. They mentioned party
reform, the adoption of mixed district elections, campaign finance reform,
and changes to increase the number of congressmen in highly-populated states
which are under-represented in Congress.
Abstention rates were not immediately available, but the lack of queues at
polling booths seemed to indicate a low turnout even though voters are
required by law to cast ballots. A pre-election poll showed 57 per cent
would not vote if not obliged to.
</TEXT>
