<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 93 / The Balkan Conflict: Milosevic deaf to Owen entreaties
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER and ROBERT MAUTHNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
LORD OWEN, the European Community mediator, yesterday failed in his
eleventh-hour effort to persuade Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic to
swing his weight behind the international peace plan for Bosnia.
During a one-day visit to Belgrade, Lord Owen made what many observers see
as a final attempt to persuade Mr Milosevic to bring Bosnian Serb leaders to
heel and support the plan, devised by himself and Mr Cyrus Vance, to divide
Bosnia into 10 provinces, roughly along ethnic lines.
After a 2 1/2 -hour session behind closed doors, Mr Fred Eckhard, spokesman
for the mediators, admitted little hope remained that Serb leaders would
drop their opposition to the plan.
He said: 'I don't want to say last chance, but there's a particular pressure
now on everybody to see if something can't be pulled out at the last
minute.' Lord Owen, who also held talks with President Dobrica Cosic of the
rump Yugoslavia, is due to return to Belgrade tomorrow for talks with
President Milosevic, Mr Radovan Karadzic, the Bosnian Serb leader, and the
Bosnian Serb military commander Ratko Mladic.
Mr Eckhard, admitting the failure to overcome fierce Serb objections to the
plan, said: 'If the Serbs say 'no' as they have done today, they (Lord Owen
and Mr Vance) have no option really but to turn it over to the Security
Council.'
The disarmament of Moslems in Srebrenica, the besieged eastern Bosnian town,
was completed and the town demilitarised by noon yesterday, the UN said.
But a Bosnian Serb army leader claimed Moslems had reneged on an agreement
to give up weapons and had handed in only a small quantity of arms, 'mostly
outdated and unusable'.
</TEXT>
