<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 93 / Drug sales fall after Bonn health reforms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ABRAHAMS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FRANCE overtook Germany as western Europe's largest prescription drugs
market in the first two months of the year, according to data from IMS
International, the specialist pharmaceuticals market research company.
German sales have been affected by a price freeze. The market has fallen
about 15 per cent since healthcare reforms introduced at the beginning of
January.
The company estimates sales in the seven largest western European markets -
which represent about 85 per cent of the whole western European market -
were Dollars 7.32bn (Pounds 4.84bn) during January and February.
Purchases by pharmacies - about 80 per cent of total drugs sales - reached
Dollars 2.09bn in France compared with Dollars 1.6bn in Germany.
Italy was the third largest market with sales of Dollars 1.59bn, followed by
Spain (Dollars 783m), the UK (Dollars 758m), and Belgium (Dollars 253m).
Sales in the Netherlands were estimated at Dollars 248m, although the figure
was extrapolated from January data. The figures exclude sales to hospitals.
The biggest selling type of drug were cardiovascular medicines, although
sales were down 2 per cent at Dollars 1.52bn. Alimentary and metabolism
drugs, which include ulcer treatments, dropped 1 per cent to Dollars 1.24bn.
Respiratory medicines were static at Dollars 756m.
However, anti-infectives, which include anti-virals and antibiotics,
increased 6 per cent to Dollars 805m, while central nervous system
treatments increased 2 per cent to Dollars 800m.
IMS International figures for 1992 suggest the seven countries had sales of
Dollars 49bn, up 8 per cent on 1991.
Cardiovascular sales were up 7 per cent at Dollars 10.86bn, alimentary and
metabolism increased 8 per cent at Dollars 8.34bn, central nervous system
rose 9 per cent to Dollars 5.32bn, anti-infectives increased 9 per cent to
Dollars 4.46bn, and musculo-skeletal were up 5 per cent at Dollars 2.82bn.
The fastest growing areas were cytostatics, used to treat cancer, up 20 per
cent at Dollars 1.15bn, and blood and organ treatments up 13 per cent at
Dollars 2.5bn.
