<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 93 / Major to join attack on EBRD spending
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS, ROBERT PESTON and PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR, the prime minister, is expected on Monday to use the keynote
address of the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development annual
meeting to criticise the bank for its lavish spending on new London offices.
He is also expected to back the call from Mr Theo Waigel, Germany's finance
minister, for greater openness at the bank when he addresses the EBRD's
governors' meeting on Monday in London.
Mr Major's criticisms are expected to be diplomatically worded but indicate
government concern that the bank has acted insensitively. It also emerged
yesterday that Mr Don McCutchan, the only director of the EBRD to vote
against its 1993 budget, is being removed a year and a half earlier than he
expected.
Mr McCutchan, a Canadian, has been one of the most consistent critics of the
bank's expenditure on its office furnishings, parties, entertaining and
administration.
On December 14, he was the only director to vote against the 1993 budget of
Ecu136m (Pounds 108m) for administrative expenses, up from Ecu103.5m in the
previous year. The bank's 23 directors are public officials representing the
56 countries and international agencies which own the bank. On March 5, Mr
Jacques Attali, the bank's president, and Mr Brian Mulroney, the Canadian
prime minister, met in Ottawa.
An EBRD director said that days later, Canadian officials arrived at the
bank to conduct an inquiry into Mr McCutchan's fitness as a director.
EBRD directors said Mr McCutchan was exonerated by the report. 'If anything,
it made him appear too good, like Mother Teresa,' commented a director.
A Canadian government spokesman said yesterday that Mr McCutchan would hold
his post until this summer and then return to Canada as part of the normal
rotation of diplomatic officers. However, a friend of Mr McCutchan said he
had not been expecting to return to Canada until the summer of 1994.
The EBRD refused to make any comment on Mr McCutchan. At the weekend, Mr
Attali said Mr Mulroney had 'just telephoned me to express his support',
after widespread criticisms that the bank's internal expenditure had run out
of control in its first two years of operation.
Mr Attali yesterday met Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor. Mr Lamont said the
bank's audit committee, composed of eight directors and independent of the
bank's day-to-day management, should inquire thoroughly and quickly into
reports of excessive spending on fitting out the bank's new headquarters in
London and other costs, such as hiring private aircraft to ferry Mr Attali
to appointments.
Britain supports demands by directors that the committee should have
external help in carrying out its investigation rather than relying on the
internal auditors used normally by the bank. The outside help could be
provided by a firm of accountants or chartered surveyors.
During the meeting, Mr Lamont said it was vital the issues raised by the
EBRD's spending did not interfere with its efforts to help establish
market-based economies in eastern Europe and the former Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
