<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 93 / MPs vote against treaty referendum
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MPs early this morning voted decisively against a British referendum on the
Maastricht treaty, marking a further victory for the government over Tory
and Labour Euro-sceptics.
The rejection of a referendum by a majority of 239 votes came as the Commons
was expected today to complete its detailed line-by-line consideration of
the Maastricht bill, which it began last December.
Although a comfortable win had been expected, the vote is an important
milestone in the government's battle to secure ratification of the treaty
and will come as a welcome boost to its morale.
Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign secretary, argued that to allow Britain's final
verdict on Maastricht to be delivered in a referendum and not by parliament
would amount to 'a shirking of the responsibilities' MPs were given in the
general election last April.
Labour's front bench made common cause with the government by voting against
a referendum but opposition came from Euro-sceptics in both leading parties.
The Liberal Democrats were split, with about half voting for a referendum.
The result, delivered just after 2am, left referendum supporters pinning
their hopes on the House of Lords where a debate on the subject  - with the
possibility of a less clear-cut outcome - is anticipated in June or July.
Lady Thatcher, the former prime minister, and Lord Tebbit, the former
Conservative party chairman, are expected to spearhead a campaign in favour
of a referendum when the bill reaches the upper house after its third
Commons reading later this summer.
Lord Healey, former Labour chancellor, this week served warning that the
Lords vote could present a significant obstacle to the government's plans
when he said its recent Commons manoeuvrings had made 'a lot of people like
myself' more inclined to vote for a referendum.
The government's next concern will be to shepherd the bill through its
Commons report stage, which it hopes to complete before the second Danish
referendum on Maastricht on May 18.
Labour still hopes to use this stage to corner the government into embracing
the treaty's social chapter.
If the Danes vote Yes, a third Commons reading would be expected to follow
before the end of May.
Cross-party unity thwarts referendum move, Page 12
</TEXT>
