<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 93 / Christies buys City art and coin dealer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CHRISTIES International, the auctioneer, yesterday bought Spink and Son, its
neighbour in the heart of London's art market and one of the oldest of the
City's fine art dealers.
The sale is worth up to Pounds 16.3m to Andrew Weir, the private shipping
and hotels company that owned Spink, and is significantly below the Pounds
50m sought in 1990 when the company first went on to the market before the
Gulf war.
While Christies' purchase has been taken as further confirmation of faint
stirrings in the art market, it also demonstrates the extent to which the
market has fallen.
The deal will involve Christies in some little-known duties in addition to
giving it an ability to deal in fine art coins, medals and oriental works.
Spink, as official medallist to the Royal Household, has to ensure that the
Queen and Prince Philip are correctly attired with medals and other
decorations on public occasions. It will continue to trade under the name
Spink from its premises in King Street, St James's. But the deal marks
another change of fortune for a company founded in the City of London in
1666, the year of the Great Fire.
Its more recent record, however, has been patchy. From a profit in 1989 of
Pounds 2.1m, the company was making similar losses within two years. Last
year it made losses of Pounds 700,000 on sales of Pounds 21.7m at the
trading level.
The sale of Spink will also raise questions in the art world as to whether
there is a potential conflict of interest. Christies, as an auctioneer,
would be expected to sell at the highest price possible, while Spink, might
be expected to want to buy at the lowest.
Lord Carrington, Christies International chairman, will chair a compliance
committee to ensure what the company calls a 'proper separation and
identity' of Christies and Spink.
Christies is paying an initial Pounds 7.1m in cash and to settle
inter-company debts. It will also pay up to Pounds 1.7m if Spink's tax
losses are realised and up to Pounds 7.7m as and when the company's stock is
sold. Christies will retain Pounds 3.9m from the sale proceeds of these
assets.
Saleroom, Page 8
Hammer falls, Page 26
</TEXT>
