<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 93 / International Company News: Sun slips in third term despite
record sales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SUN Microsystems, the leading computer workstation manufacturer, reported a
bigger than expected decline in third-quarter earnings, in spite of record
revenues. Net income for the quarter was Dollars 51.7m, or 47 cents a share,
compared with Dollars 61.4m, or 60 cents, a year earlier. Revenues for the
quarter were Dollars 1.1bn, up 20 per cent from Dollars 952m.
Sun attributed the decline to higher shipments of less profitable upgrade
products, including add-on memory and data storage devices. The company said
that European markets had been weak.
'Profitability was below the year-ago level due to gross margin declines
that were partially offset by tightly controlled growth in operating
expenses,' said Mr Kevin Melia, chief financial officer.
'Our commitment to control headcount and spending enabled us to increase
revenue per employee above Dollars 300,000 for the first time.'
For the first nine months of fiscal 1993, Sun recorded revenues of Dollars
3.1bn, up 17 per cent from the same period a year earlier. Net income for
the nine-month period was Dollars 80.6m, or 77 cents a share, compared with
Dollars 135.6m, or Dollars 1.34, last year.
