<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 93 / International Company News: Earnings per share up at GTE
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GTE, the largest local US telephone company, yesterday reported a 12 per
cent rise in first-quarter earnings per share, excluding accounting changes,
thanks to higher volumes and lower costs in its telephone operations and
strong growth in its cellular telephone business.
The company reported consolidated net income of Dollars 460m, or 48 cents a
share, compared with earnings per share of 43 cents a year ago.
After adjusting the 1992 earnings for a change in accounting rules for
retirees' health benefits, the group had a net loss in the first quarter of
last year of Dollars 2.05bn, or Dollars 2.27 a share.
Sales and revenues in the latest quarter totalled Dollars 4.83bn, against
Dollars 4.82bn a year ago, while operating income was up 9 per cent at
Dollars 1.10bn.
Revenues from telephone operations rose from Dollars 3.85bn to Dollars
3.92bn and operating income was up 7 per cent at Dollars 1.04bn.
Revenues and sales from telecommunications products and services dipped 6
per cent to Dollars 911m. Operating income rose from Dollars 29m to Dollars
60m.
Sprint, the third largest US long-distance carrier, reported a net loss of
Dollars 413m, or Dollars 1.21 a share, compared with profits of Dollars
128m, or 38 cents, after the cost of changing its accounting methods for
retirees' health benefits, and Dollars 248m of costs associated with its
takeover of Centel, the Chigaco-based phone company.
However, the company said income from continuing operations, excluding
special charges, was Dollars 154m, or 45 cents, compared with Dollars 106m,
or 31 cents, in the first quarter of last year. Revenues rose 9 per cent to
Dollars 2.72bn.
