<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 93 / International Company News: UAP chief sees sell-off despite
71% fall in profit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR JEAN Peyrelevade, president of UAP, France's largest insurer, believes
the privatisation of the state-owned insurance group will go ahead this
autumn in spite of a 71 per cent fall last year to FFr1.08bn (Dollars 200m)
in profits and a cut in dividend to FFr8 a share from FFr11.
The UAP chief forecast that the Balladur government's sell-off programme
would not get under way until the autumn, by which time UAP's results for
the first of 1993 would be in.
Mr Peyrelevade said he could not foresee a repetition of 1992's 'avalanche
of catastrophes and troubles'. For UAP, these ranged from the costs of
Hurricane Andrew in the US, a sharp rise in French car thefts, to
property-related losses incurred by the Banque Worms, its French banking
subsidiary and by Danish insurers in which UAP has direct and indirect
stakes.
In spite of an earlier warning that profits would be sharply down from
1991's level of FFr3.76bn, UAP shares were briefly suspended yesterday to
allow the market to digest news of the dividend cut.
Mr Peyrelevade conceded UAP's error in getting involved in Danish insurance
at a time of instability in Scandinavian financial markets. UAP last year
suffered a FFr400m loss because of its indirect holding in Baltica.
Yesterday, UAP said it had set aside provisions to cover its FFr270m direct
stake in Hafnia, another Danish insurer.
The UAP president said it was not clear that his group would want to sell
Banque Worms, even after the banking subsidiary was restored to health. Last
year, the bank lost FFr1.64bn and UAP injected nearly FFr1.5bn of capital
into the institution.
Mr Peyrelevade said UAP was under growing pressure from banks selling life
insurance policies directly to their clients, and that it might be useful
for the insurance group to retain a banking operation.
</TEXT>
