FT  21 APR 93 / UK Company News: Lasmo chiefs take 5% cut
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Lasmo executive directors will take a 5 per cent pay cut this year, the oil
exploration company said yesterday.
The announcement followed the annual report's publication showing that the
remuneration of Mr Chris Greentree, former chief executive, increase by 40
per cent last year to Pounds 480,647. The company incurred a loss of Pounds
385m and cut its dividend, but Mr Greentree received a Pounds 50,000
performance-related pay bonus.
Lasmo has also proposed issuing Dollars 150m (Pounds 99m) of cumulative
preference shares in the US and up to Dollars 250m of long-term fixed rate
debt securities or Yankee bonds. The company said it would count the
perpetual preference shares as equity and expected gearing to fall by 20
percentage points to 68 per cent.
Other annual reports showed that Mr Tom Farmer, chairman of Kwik-Fit
Holdings, had his pay reduced from Pounds 342,000 to Pounds 234,000 as
pre-tax profits fell from Pounds 32m to Pounds 17m.
Sir David Alliance, chairman of Coats Viyella, picked up more at Pounds
218,000 (Pounds 193,000) but Mr Neville Bain, chief executive, received less
at Pounds 352,000, including Pounds 17,000 performance-related incentive
payments, compared with Pounds 381,000. Coats Viyella pre-tax profits for
1992 were Pounds 109m, against Pounds 111m published.
