<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 93 / IBM reports loss of Dollars 285m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
INTERNATIONAL Business Machines yesterday reported a Dollars 285m (Pounds
188m) first-quarter loss, providing little hope for a short-term recovery by
the world's largest computer company. Its losses were almost Dollars 5bn
last year, its worst ever.
IBM said European sales dropped sharply in the first quarter, by almost 14
per cent, with 3 per cent declines in the US and Asia. World-wide sales of
IBM's core mainframe computer products were down by a 'high double-digit per
cent'.
One bright spot was a 48 per cent increase in service revenues, which rose
to Dollars 1.9bn.
Mr Louis Gerstner, IBM's new chairman and chief executive, who joined from
RJR Nabisco on April 1, said the results 'reflect weak demand and continued
competitive pressures in many of our hardware product lines, particularly
mainframe computers and large disk drives'.
Overall, revenues declined to Dollars 13.1bn from Dollars 14bn while losses
per share were 50 cents, in line with Wall Street's expectations.
In the first quarter of 1992, IBM posted net earnings of Dollars 2.5bn,
including a gain of Dollars 1.9bn from the adoption of a new tax accounting
standard. Earnings per share were Dollars 1.12, or Dollars 4.45 including
the one-time gain. Gross profit margins fell to 39.5 per cent, down from
50.8 per cent in the first quarter last year.
IBM said it would continue to 'aggressively seek ways to improve the
company's profitability,' but Mr Gerstner had no comment on what form these
actions might take. In his first public appearance since taking over at IBM,
Mr Gerstner will address the company's annual meeting in Florida next week.
IBM said operating expenses declined by 8.9 per cent in the first quarter to
Dollars 5.4bn, and expenses were expected to continue to decline as the
company reduced its workforce. It has said it would eliminate 25,000 jobs
this year.
The group personal computers achieved profitability. Sales of computer
workstations also grew strongly. However, total hardware sales fell to
Dollars 5.7bn, against Dollars 7.1bn. Rental and financing revenues, driven
by mainframe computer installations, were down 12 per cent at Dollars 1.1bn,
while maintenance services fell by 5 per cent to Dollars 1.8bn.
